1. DOCKER ANSWERS
1.create folder and move into it

$ mkdir b20244
$ cd b20244
$ pwd
$nano index.html

2.Create an index.html file
#!/bin/bash

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Nginx Docker Test</title>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Hello! This page is served from an NGINX Docker container.</h1>
  <p>Question 3 — simple demo.</p>
</body>
</html>

cat index.html

3.Create a dockerfile

#!/bin/bash
# Use the official nginx image based on Alpine Linux (small)
FROM nginx:alpine

# Copy our index.html into the location nginx serves by default
COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/

# Document that the container listens on port 80
EXPOSE 80

cat dockerfile

4.build the docker image
# Run this in the same folder (the . means current directory):

docker build -t mynginx:1.0.

# What it does: Docker reads the Dockerfile and creates an image named mynginx:1.0.

Run the container
docker run -d --name mynginx_container -p 8080:80 mynginx:1.0

output:
# $ docker run -d --name mynginx_container -p 8080:80 mynginx:1.0
# f594410e28d0d850a506868b6489ebb97bd0b64af2192f7e729febdc43308780


$ docker ps (to verify container is running)
# CONTAINER ID   IMAGE         COMMAND                  CREATED              STATUS              PORTS                                     NAMES
# f594410e28d0   mynginx:1.0   "/docker-entrypoint.…"   About a minute ago   Up About a minute   0.0.0.0:8080->80/tcp, [::]:8080->80/tcp   mynginx_container

Type in browser: http://localhost:8080



